    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, thanks. i remember my prof mentioning something about it being \"spooky\" though? like i think the quote was something about \"spooky action at a distance.\" why did he call it spooky? is there something weird or unexplained about the mechanics of it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"spooky action at a distance\" phrase is indeed a famous quote from Albert Einstein, who was initially skeptical of entanglement. He felt that the instantaneous correlation between entangled particles was too fast, too precise, and too unexplained by classical physics. It's like the particles are \"talking\" to each other in a way that defies space and time, which Einstein found unsettling.\n\nThe weirdness of entanglement lies in the fact that it seems to violate our classical intuition about space and time. According to classical physics, information can't travel faster than the speed of light, but entanglement suggests that information can be transmitted instantaneously between particles, regardless of the distance between them. This is known as \"quantum non-locality\" or \"spooky action at a distance.\"\n\nIt's a bit like the idea of a messenger being sent to a distant location, but instead of using a physical path, the message is transmitted directly from one particle to the other, without any physical medium. This is a fundamental aspect of quantum mechanics that challenges our understanding of reality and has led to many interesting debates and discussions in the field.",
      "source": "target",
